Climate resistance brakes the economy
In the first year of Mario López Valdez's government, unemployment and black labour rose in Sinaloa, while foreign investment declined and the economy stagnated.
2011 will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloas. It is the first year in which Mario López Valdez, who called himself the initiator of the change and had great hopes about economic growth, is at the government. However, due to the climate constraints, growth cannot be the word, but instead the main economic indicators have worsened.
The low temperatures in February not only resulted in losses of millions in agriculture, but also raised close limits to the growth of the state economy and caused a general decline in economic activity by 3.6% in the first quarter of the year. This is mainly due to the historical decline in agricultural development by 31.16%, which has a slowdown in other sectors.
According to a report by the Council of Mexicoo para el Development Rural Sustainable (the Mexican Council for Sustainable Agricultural Development) on the effects of frost, 582,000 hectares of agriculturally used land were damaged, 78.03 percent of which were completely destroyed and the rest 21.07 percent were mainly affected by vegetable, maize and peanut cultivation.
The decline in economic activity until November has allowed unemployment to rise continuously in the Mexican state. In the first quarter of the year, the Instituto Nacional de Estadostica y Geografía observed a rapid increase in unemployment, since from January to March 55,053 people in Sinaloa had no employment, corresponding to 4.53 per cent of the working population. In the second quarter, unemployment rates rose to 5.28 per cent and from July to 6.19 per cent, resulting in 74 000 unemployed in Sinaloa. These are 18 969 people over the first quarter.
Lower liquidity
The unemployment rate in Sinaloa in the year goes back to several factors. Economic scientist Gerardo López Cervantes, Dean of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the University of Autónoma (UAS), comments that public institutions' policies declare the growing unemployment indirectly.
"What we are currently observing is an increase in unemployment that has to do with several factors. Among other things, with liquidity losses on the market due to the cuts in the legislation adopted to combat money laundering in Congress, because it is not easy to let these work for themselves to invest or use for something else," he said.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that the growing unemployment is also a demographic factor.
"The number of people who leave the country looking for work abroad, especially in the United States, has declined. This is due to the problems of entry and because it is also difficult to find work there. These people stay here and look for work here, which leads to rising unemployment," he says.
Black work
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is even more serious when considering the high proportion of black labour. This includes 60.38% of the people employed in the country who work without paying into the social insurance boxes.
The low wages, the lowest in all of Mexico, are due to unemployment and black labour, according to the statistics of the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexico Social Insurance Institute) and the Secretariat of Labour y Previsión Social (Government Office for Labour and Social Welfare in Mexico).
The average monthly income of workers in Sinaloa was up to September 5352 pesos; this is much less than the overall average of 7375 pesos.
ADI decrease
In addition to reducing economic activity and increasing unemployment, the highest decrease in foreign direct investment (ADI) over the last ten years is recorded in 2011. According to the Secretariat de Economía (State Economic Authority), the ADI was between January and June 630 597 dollars, which corresponds to a total of 87.74 percent compared to the $5,143,312 in the same period in the previous year.
On the other hand, the Secretariat of Economic Development (Government Authority for Economic Development) lists a total investment of 17 280 000 pesos in 2011, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
The Debts
In view of the economic crisis, in July the Government applied for a loan of 3 000 000 000 pesos to be invested in reactivation of the economy in infrastructure projects in the 18 communities. The country congress approved an amount of 200 600,000 pesos, but no positive effects on any of the economic sectors in the country could be found by November.
Reactions
For the representatives of the company, the first year of government, Mario López Valdé's inability to government was revealed.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación (State Chamber of Processing Industry in Mexico), said that no efforts were made in 2011 to harmonise the views of the different sectors, including the government.
"The economic activity in Sinaloa was really nice this year. It has to be worked hard to get the land lost this year and we have to work hard twice as hard in 2012. The efforts of all and especially the progress of the already well-agreed government teams have not been sufficiently coordinated," he said.
Slow economic development
Loredo López said that events such as frost at the beginning of the year made economic development difficult and slowed down.
"The low economic flow is the result of several events, including frost. One of the most important effects is a slow economy that is not moving enough to generate an economic dynamic that could produce an acceptable flow of processes, products and services. That is why we will close the year far below our expectations," he said.
Redefine Call
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederation of employers of the Mexican Republic, explained in Sinaloa that the state had to engage in more dynamic productive activities.
"In general, we have observed that work has been done. We believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term programme to redefine the economic vocation and line of the country, because it is important to activate all material and human resources Sinaloas," he said.
There's a lot to do
The President of Coparmex stressed how important it is to develop a future perspective that is linked to the efforts of the government in better railways.
"In general, I would say that the government has achieved good results in various areas. Economic development has progressed, but it is important to develop a long-term programme," he said.
He stressed that the current government had made progress with the government.
"There are areas where it can be said that the government has acted more comprehensively. What I can say is that it has been worked and that the government is aware that there is still a lot of work ahead of it," he said.
