The Court approves the transition to digital television in Mexico for 2015
The conversion of analogues to digital signals in recent years is one of the most important changes in the world.
The Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) showed the constitutional appeals brought by the Senate and the House of Deputies against the Presidential Class and the power to bring forward the switchover of analogues to digital signals from 2021 to 2015, due to the lack of eight votes required to challenge the law.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Supreme Court, Juan Silva Meza, were of the view that President Felipe Calderón did not go beyond his responsibilities when he issued the Bill with details on the switch to the terrestrial digital television.
This decision rejected the constitutional dispute raised by the Senate, since it did not receive the required qualified majority of eight votes in order to enable the court to decide on the constitutionality or non-constitutionality.
In the draft complaint prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, it was proposed to declare the Decree of Law against the Constitution, since the Commission Federal de Telecommunications (Cofetel) (Federal Commission for Telecommunications in Mexico) is responsible for the radio and television regulations, so the Decree of Law would oppose the principles of hierarchy and the provisions of law.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted in favour of the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies filed constitutional complaints against the Legislative Decree. Following the adoption of the complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero no longer appealed to the Legislative Decree and introduced all activities to establish the digital transfer.
The Council of Ministers also rejected the complaint submitted by the Chamber of Deputies, without taking part in the debate on the project for which Minister Sánchez Cordero was also responsible.
In his contribution, the President-in-Office said that he did not agree with the project's arguments and that the country's government was not allowed to regulate the measures to be taken by the public administration in general.
"I also do not believe that if this were to be done, the independence of the regulatory body would be affected." She also recalled that the central government is responsible for planning strategic policy areas, such as the telecommunications sector, for constitutional reasons, because this leads to state affairs.
The replacement of analogue signals by digital is one of the most important changes that have occurred in recent years around the world, and it makes better use of the radio spectrum, increased signal quality and more channels.
The postponement of the conversion meant that it was a postponement of the use of digitalisation, which was a decision in the public interest, which not only had technical views, "because it encompasses economic, social, political and security aspects."
These issues, she stressed, "required the whole system to act, in accordance with the principle of economic governance by the State, they contained a group of features that put the Constitution into the hands of the central government."
She recalled that many countries around the world had already made the digital change, although they had highly specialized facilities.
It cannot be concluded that the government would intervene in Congress's jurisdiction by issuing the contested decree, because the laws adopted by the legislation would be respected," she said.
The possibility of counting the voting lists in Michoacán is taken into consideration.
According to PREP, the difference between the first and the second seats in the election of the Governor is almost 27 percent, with 879 votes of 6074 not yet counted.
The possibility of counting the voting lists is a reality this year in the elections in Michoacán, because according to the data issued by the Program de Resultados Electorales Preliminares (PREP), the difference between the first and second seats in the governors' elections is almost 27 percent, with 879 votes of 6074 not yet counted.
In this regard, the President of the Council General del Instituto Electoral de Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llenderal Zaragoza, recalled that, just last November, the polling station had adopted a number of regulations to harmonise local regulations with the reforms of the federal states in outstanding matters.
It should be recalled that Michoacán had not adapted neither his political constitution nor his election law nor his law on electoral justice to the reforms adopted by the Congress, so that they did not come into force at this round of elections. Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel avoided publication in the public display within the time limits for this to be set with the argument or objections.
On 9 November, the Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) decided on the constitutional complaint filed by the local legislation and judged the State Representative's vote on the constitutional reforms as "invalid and illegal", since he did not have the right to "conclusion or vote against it".
Maria de los Ángeles Llanderal explained in an interview on the possibility of counting the votes individually, that, thanks to the adoption of the directives by the Council General del IEM, the possibility of the local electoral authority being able to count the voting list in part or in full.
Thus, under the following conditions, the votes contained in one or more electoral packages may not be counted in part. The results in the minutes do not agree; the vote count and calculation protocol is not in force or is not owned by the chairman of the electoral committee or there are obvious errors or changes in the protocols.
In addition, the total number of fully completed ballots may be counted if there is a difference between the moderate winner and the second winner, which is equal to or less than one per cent, provided that at the beginning of the meeting there is an express request from the Party or the Coalition Chairman, who is the second of those candidates.
The vote count may also take place in its entirety if, after completion of the proper calculation, it is established that the difference between the moderate winner and the candidate in the second place is equal to or less than one per cent, subject to an explicit request by a representative of the party whose candidate has become the second. In this case, the electoral packages which were subject to a partial count would be excluded.
It is worth mentioning that the elections in Morelia are in the same situation where, according to the PREP, the difference between the first and the second seats is almost 0.16 per cent, although the votes of 129 of the total of 923 electoral protocols have not yet been counted.
