UNAM Asphalt Prevents Hits
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at UNAM University of Mexico, develops modified asphalts with polymers to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
If the signs from the road surface were to be taken into account, it would not be necessary to repair nearly 200,000 hitholes if the rainy season in the Metropolitana del Valle de México area of the valley of Mexico broke out, Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at UNAM University, warned and ensured that if the clearance and maintenance of the asphalt surface are adequately reduced or even completely avoided.
In his presentation "Technical blowholes", which he held on the occasion of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible develops asphalt modified with polymers to produce a mixture similar to the asphalt, but which has a greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Mr Nájera believed that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climates, such as in some cities in the north of the country, in order to improve the behaviour of the road surface and to avoid the occurrence of shock holes.
He explained that the asphalt - the most difficult part of the oil - is a hydrocarbon compound from which one part has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphalts - and the other part a low - the so-called malthene. Together, they give the road surface its characteristic numerical behavior.
The numerical behavior of the asphalt means that it behaves at high temperatures of almost 180°C as a liquid, at 120°C it is very fluid and at 50°C, while it is broken at very low temperatures.
"This means that the resistance of asphalt on the streets is not the same, but changes on one day depending on weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," the chemical engineer concluded.
The FQ researcher noted that the streets of Mexico City had mostly a flexible road cover consisting of six layers of material, the last three of which contained asphalt.
Between the top layers is a layer of asphalt, which consists of small, asphalt-bathed and then solidified stones.
Each single stone of this wear layer has been bathed in asphalt.
If the vehicles move on and forces are generated, this layer enables a good distribution of power in the road cover.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would be even better distributed," said the chemical engineer.
"On the layer of wear," he said, "a last layer is designed, the so-called layer of wear consisting of small stones, i.e. sand, which was also bathed in asphalt.
Since these layers are in contact with the tyres, they need a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and they need to produce friction.
This road cover receives and distributes most of the forces, also requires a suitable thickness and the material from which it is made must be maintained.
The weather conditions, in particular humidity and temperature fluctuations, are further important factors, especially water", he said, "because it affects the conduct of the wear layer significantly.
When the ground is wet, water enters into the layer and only becomes difficult again. This causes a diversion of all layers of the road surface and consequently the appearance of impact holes.
When a blowhole occurs, he said, "the cover layer will be removed first, while the wear layer will only be affected afterwards. But the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that should be maintained by appropriate maintenance programs at the first signs."
The member in the System Nacional de Investigadores (National Research System Mexico) explained that the vehicle load is another important reason for the occurrence of impactors. Therefore, the thickness of each layer of the road surface should always be relative to the vehicle load and it should be ensured that this system is respected to avoid frequent impactors.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that many research work was still pending, for example on asphalt emulsions, which were already on the market in other countries, and with which the impactors could easily and simply repair themselves without applying high temperatures.
